We need to prove `AEMeasurable (fun ω => G ω ⊓ H ω) P`. 

To show this, we need to prove that for any set `A` in the σ-algebra on `SimpleGraph V`, the preimage `(fun ω => G ω ⊓ H ω)⁻¹(A)` is measurable. 

The set `(fun ω => G ω ⊓ H ω)⁻¹(A)` is the set of `ω` such that `G ω ⊓ H ω ∈ A`. 

Since `G` and `H` are binomial random graphs, they are AEMeasurable. This means that for any Borel set `B`, the sets `{ω | G ω ∈ B}` and `{ω | H ω ∈ B}` are measurable.

To show that `{ω | G ω ⊓ H ω ∈ A}` is measurable, we can express it as a countable union of sets of the form `{ω | G ω ∈ B₁, H ω ∈ B₂}` where `B₁` and `B₂` are chosen such that their intersection is the set of graphs in `A`.

